Crate root for `ctx-cage`, the sandboxing layer that isolates an autonomous agent run's blast radius (filesystem, host namespaces, network) — not a content-filtering or tool-brokering layer. That role moved to `ctx-context`; the agent uses native Read/Edit inside the cage.

Re-exports submodules `bwrap`, `cli`, `error`, `lifecycle`, `proxy`, `runtime` — this file itself has no logic, just doc-level architecture description and two embedded assets. `CAGE_RULES_MD` is agent doctrine injected via `--append-system-prompt-file` on every real `claude` launch; it's `include_str!`'d so it's physically impossible to ship a binary without it — if `assets/cage-rules.md` is deleted, the crate fails to compile rather than silently launching an unconstrained agent.

`CAGE_RESOLV_CONF` is a stub `resolv.conf` bound into every cage; since the cage is fully offline (`--unshare-net`), it never resolves anything — its only purpose is making DNS lookups fail slowly rather than instantly, per ADR-049 (see the asset file's own comment for rationale).

Key invariants documented here but enforced elsewhere: workspace is the only read-write mount, bound at its real host path with no fixed alias (ADR-046); secrets (`.env`, `.git/config`) are masked even inside the workspace; nothing from `$HOME` is mounted; the real API key never enters the cage — only the host-side `proxy` module injects it, reached via a bind-mounted UNIX socket. `no_new_privs` is set unconditionally by bwrap; a seccomp filter is a documented gap, not yet implemented — don't assume syscall filtering exists.